ary expressions of piety and devotion, and American popular culture. Ranging from portrayals of environmental sin and virtue such as the eco-pious depiction of Christian Grey in Fifty Shades of Grey, to the green capitalism found in the world of mobile-device “carbon sin-tracking” software applications, to the socially conscious vegetarian vampires in True Blood, the volume illuminates the work pop culture performs as both a mirror and an engine for the greening of American spiritual and ethical commitments. Taylor makes the case that it is not through a framework of grim duty or obligation, but through one of play and delight, that we may move environmental ideals into substantive action.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEcologyxReligious aspects. 0aEcology-Religious aspects. 0aEcotheology. 0aMass mediaxReligious aspects. 0aMass media-Religious aspects. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh  aMars colonization.  aSpaceX.  aToyota.  aabstaining.  acapitalism.  acarbon.  acivic engagement.  aconsumer products.  aconsumer.  aconsumption.  adeath denial.  adecoding.  adisposability.  aeco-funeral.  aeconomy.  aecoplay.  aencoding.  aendangered species.  aenvironmental.  agreen burial.  agreen capitalism.  agreening.  agreenwashed.  agreenwashing.  aindividualized.  ainterventions.  amedia interventions.  amediated popular culture.  amoral engagement.  amoral foundations theory.  amoral interventions.  amoral self-licensing.  amoral sphere.  amortality.  aobligation.  aoffsetting.  aoppositional narratives.  apolicy.  apollution porn.  areality TV.  aregulation.  areinhabiting.  asocial change.  astorytelling.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Packa